T1  - Conducting R&D in Countries with Weak Intellectual Property Rights Protection
AU  - Zhao, Minyuan
Y1  - 2006/08/01
PY  - 2006
DA  - 2006/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.1060.0516
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.1060.0516
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 1185
EP  - 1199
VL  - 52
IS  - 8
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - Multinational enterprises (MNEs) are increasingly conducting research and development (R MNEs that possess alternative mechanisms for protecting their intellectual properties will therefore find it attractive to conduct R&D at those locations. A theoretical framework is developed to capture the interaction between firm strategy and the institutional environment. The empirical analysis on a sample of 1,567 U.S.-headquartered innovating firms finds results consistent with the hypotheses that (i) technologies developed in countries with weak IPR protection are used more internally, and (ii) technologies developed by firms with R&D in weak IPR countries show stronger internal linkages. The results suggest that firms may use internal organizations to substitute for inadequate external institutions. By doing so, they are able to take advantage of the arbitrage opportunities presented by the institutional gap across countries.
AB  - Multinational enterprises (MNEs) are increasingly conducting research and development (R MNEs that possess alternative mechanisms for protecting their intellectual properties will therefore find it attractive to conduct R&D at those locations. A theoretical framework is developed to capture the interaction between firm strategy and the institutional environment. The empirical analysis on a sample of 1,567 U.S.-headquartered innovating firms finds results consistent with the hypotheses that (i) technologies developed in countries with weak IPR protection are used more internally, and (ii) technologies developed by firms with R&D in weak IPR countries show stronger internal linkages. The results suggest that firms may use internal organizations to substitute for inadequate external institutions. By doing so, they are able to take advantage of the arbitrage opportunities presented by the institutional gap across countries.
